BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Dr. Andreas Baer\, KIT Maximal performance! This used to be the goal for research software for HPC\, but sustainability is getting more and more traction and growing importance. This course targets two aspects contributing to sustainable research software for HPC clusters: Firstly\, energy and carbon optimization in the usage is outlined to raise awareness and make the participants ready for future HPC systems with energy-budget-based resource grants or efficiency rewarding queuing systems as pioneered by Japans #1 supercomputer Fugaku. Secondly\, sustainability in the development process of HPC research software is addressed\, where productivity\, code quality and carbon efficiency often go hand in hand. The course is specifically targeted to researchers using and developing HPC research software\, in all career stages\, irrespective of their usage type (e.g. physical simulations\, data analysis\, AI). It is intended as an interactive course\, allowing plenty of time for discussion and exchange on this topic\nHost: Scientific Software Center\nVenue: Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, in the conference room 5/104 on the 5th floor\nLink: https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/compact-course-sustainable-hpc\nDuration: 4h
DTEND:20260527T110000Z
LOCATION:Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, in the conference room 5/104 on the 5th floor
DTSTART:20260527T070000Z
SUMMARY:Compact course: Sustainability in Research Software for HPC
UID:e55aa375-5797-411d-8f97-f4ad1ce16109@e55a.org
URL:https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/compact-course-sustainable-hpc
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Prof. Gábor Csányi • Director Max Planck Institute for Polymer Research I will report on our latest efforts to create universally applicable machine learning force fields using the MACE architecture. Large publicly available databases (such as OMAT and OMOL) and large scale GPU compute allow the construction of force field models that cover most of the periodic table and are suitable out of the box for exploration tasks\, and in some cases (e.g. organic molecules) for accurate production level simulations. Fine tuning material models with very little effort yields near-DFT accuracy. The latest models\, such as MACE-POLAR-1 include electrostatic interactions with some notion of self-consistency\nHost: Organizer: ELLIS\, SIMPLAIX &  IWR\nVenue: Mathematikon • Conference Room\, Room 5/104\, 5th Floor • Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, 69120 Heidelberg\nLink: https://www.iwr.uni-heidelberg.de/en/events/colloquium-gabor-csanyi-2026\nDuration: 1h
DTEND:20260521T151500Z
LOCATION:Mathematikon • Conference Room\, Room 5/104\, 5th Floor • Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, 69120 Heidelberg
DTSTART:20260521T141500Z
SUMMARY:MACE Force Field Models for the Periodic Table
UID:6fda4d30-c567-442b-aa6d-fe6e2ab87b7c@6fda.org
URL:https://www.iwr.uni-heidelberg.de/en/events/colloquium-gabor-csanyi-2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Dr. Liam Keegan As agentic coding tools like Claude Code and Codex CLI make generating code faster\, validating the correctness of this code becomes more important than ever. In this course you will learn how to apply test-driven development and software testing best practices in the context of agentic software development. By writing tests before the implementation\, our test suite not only verifies correctness\, but also defines a clear specification of what the code should and should not do\nHost: Scientific Software Center\nVenue: Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, in the conference room 5/104 on the 5th floor\nLink: https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/agentic-test-driven-development\nDuration: 3h 30m
DTEND:20260723T110000Z
LOCATION:Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, in the conference room 5/104 on the 5th floor
DTSTART:20260723T073000Z
SUMMARY:Compact course: Agentic Test-Driven Development
UID:0bc8e191-aa4e-4145-b326-7691b7a3b2be@0bc8.org
URL:https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/agentic-test-driven-development
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Dr. Inga Ulusoy Generative AI is emerging as a major creative force that supports humans in content creation.  Specifically trained models can support software developers with their software projects and  lead to time savings and a shift in what aspects of generating software are more important on a day-to-day basis. In this course\, we will learn how to set up and use AI tools in software development projects. Best practices in using such tools\, as well as recommendations how to use them efficiently and safely will be introduced\nHost: Scientific Software Center\nVenue: Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, seminar room 11\nLink: https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/course-generative-ai\nDuration: 4h
DTEND:20260528T110000Z
LOCATION:Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, seminar room 11
DTSTART:20260528T070000Z
SUMMARY:Compact course: Generative AI for writing (research) software
UID:3785c982-20ef-4887-aadc-f04f22c79ad0@3785.org
URL:https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/course-generative-ai
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Dr. Dominic Kempf Applying version control can be a game changer for a collaborative research software project. However\, even in projects that already successfully use Git\, there is often room for improvement of the employed Git workflows. This workshop explores some advanced topics that increase the participants’ repertoire of Git workflows: Bisection\, Worktrees\, Submodules\, Large File Storage and Pre-commit Hooks. Additionally\, we showcase invasive methods of modifying a Git repository via Rebase\nHost: Scientific Software Center\nVenue: Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, seminar room 11\nLink: https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/compact-course-expert-git\nDuration: 4h
DTEND:20260715T110000Z
LOCATION:Mathematikon Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, seminar room 11
DTSTART:20260715T070000Z
SUMMARY:Compact course: Expert Topics in Version Control with Git
UID:1f96a2c2-2b40-4e43-aa8b-0a688101ae08@1f96.org
URL:https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/compact-course-expert-git
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DESCRIPTION:Speaker: Dr. Dominic Kempf Applying version control can be a game changer for a collaborative research software project. However\, even in projects that already successfully use Git\, there is often room for improvement of the employed Git workflows. This workshop tries to delve into collaborative workflows using Git branches and discuss their strengths. Special emphasis is given to the resolution of merge conflicts that may be required in the process of dealing with diverging branches\nHost: Scientific Software Center\nVenue: Mathematikon\, Bauteil A\, Im Neuenheimer Feld 205\, in the conference room 5/104\nLink: https://www.ssc.uni-heidelberg.de/en/compact-course-intermediate-git\nDuration: 4h
DTEND:20260708T110000Z
